          "source_section": "<completion>"
        },
        {
          "id": "g1-f2",
          "description": "`resume_required` omits the source-defined final-round budget-exhaustion mechanics: each reviewer picks one most important remaining fix, the implementer fixes only those items, and deferred items are documented in the resume result.",
          "source_section": "<completion>; Step 4.7-4.9"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Rewrite terminal states as disjoint predicates. Make `frozen` mean no deferred items and no arbitration. Make `frozen_with_conditions` require `arbitration_used = true` with only deferred minor/suggestion items. Make `resume_required` require explicit budget-exhaustion evidence, reviewer ultimatum items, the limited-fix action taken, and documented deferred findings."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-2",
      "summary": "Review mechanics do not hard-gate the required reviewer pair and carry-forward tracking is too coarse for the source negotiation model.",
      "severity": "major",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "g2-f1",
          "description": "The draft only requires a roster that satisfies the shared contract, but the source architecture for this review process says review is a `Codex + Claude pair minimum`, and the smoke contract summary also centers Codex+Claude pairs. That pair requirement is not enforced as a request-time gate here.",
          "source_section": "<inputs>; <context-gathering>; Step 1"
        },
        {
          "id": "g2-f2",
          "description": "Cross-round carry-forward is keyed to conceptual-group IDs, but the source review/fix protocol is negotiated for each reviewer finding and for each item in the implementer's fix map. Group-only carry-forward can hide unresolved sub-findings inside a reused group.",
          "source_section": "Step 4.2; Step 4.6"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Make the Codex+Claude pair an explicit validation gate for this smoke package before drafting or review launch. Track carry-forward by stable finding or fix-item IDs, with conceptual-group IDs used only as grouping metadata."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-3",
      "summary": "The draft blurs generic inherited workflow with this smoke run's executable behavior, which also makes the supplied compliance claims not credible.",
      "severity": "major",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "g3-f1",
          "description": "Step 4 is labeled `current inherited workflow` while describing reruns after rejection and split-verdict recovery, but the smoke runtime contract summary caps `max_review_rounds` at 1. The text does not separate generic architecture inheritance from what this run can actually do.",
          "source_section": "Step 4; contract summary governance/runtime"
        },
        {
          "id": "g3-f2",
          "description": "The supplied self-check/compliance claims overstate compliance for at least ARB-004, ARB-009, ARB-011, and ARB-012, because the written draft still has overlapping terminal predicates, incomplete `resume_required` semantics, group-level rather than item-level carry-forward, and no explicit Codex+Claude hard gate.",
          "source_section": "Self-check and compliance map claims versus <completion>, <inputs>, Step 4"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "For each step, distinguish inherited architecture behavior from active smoke-run behavior. If a behavior is only inherited and not executable under the current runtime budget, label it that way and point to the runtime gate. Recompute the self-check only after the text mechanically supports each claimed rule."
    }
  ],
  "fix_decisions": [],
